Siaya county assembly will Wednesday hold a special sitting to debate the BBI constitutional amendment bill. Counties within Nyanza region have started considering the draft bill a week after it was released to the 47 county assemblies. In a gazette notice by speaker George Okode, the debate will be held at the assembly chambers from 9.30 am. “Pursuant to standing order no 26 of Siaya county assembly, it is notified for the information of the members of the county assembly and general public that there shall be a special sitting of the county assembly to be held on Wednesday”. According to the notice, the business to transact include, consideration of the BBI bill 2020 and the consideration of the Siaya county finance bill 2020. On Tuesday, the assembly held public participation across all the sub-counties. In an advert last week, the assembly invited residents to attend public participation forums in all the six subcounties or submit memoranda containing their views on the bill. The pubic participation will be done on Tuesday while the memoranda was to be submitted to the office of the clerk before Tuesday. “Article 196 (1) (b) of the Constitution read together with section 87 of the County Governments Act and Standing Order 129 (3) provides for public participation and involvement in the legislative and other business of the assembly and its committees,” reads the advert signed by the assembly clerk. Already, the Kisumu county assembly has held a special sitting to debate on the bill. IEBC chairman Wafula Chebukati submitted the bill to the 47 county assemblies for approval or rejection. It will require two-thirds approval or 24 county assemblies before Kenyans can take a vote in a referendum. Chebukati said the speakers of the assemblies are required to submit the decision to speakers of the National Assembly and the Senate within three months of the date of the IEBC letter.  (Edited by Kiilu Damaris)